ive political theology that challenges both the ways we remember American history and the ways we think about the nature, meaning, and exercise of violence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aEthics, Modern. 0aPolitical theology. 0aPolitical violencexMoral and ethical aspects. 0aPolitical violencexReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aSlaveryxMoral and ethical aspectszUnited States. 4aCarl Schmitt. 4aJohn Brown. 4aWalter Benjamin. 4aexception. 4apolitical theology. 4apractical reason. 4asecularization. 4asovereignty. 4aterrorism. 7aRELIGION / Theology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479345240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804793452423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804793452.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles